        "Part (a): The submatrix `sub[P,P] D` will itself be a diagonal matrix. Its determinant will be the product of its diagonal entries. The diagonal entries of `sub[P,P] D` are `d (P.orderEmbOfFin rfl i)` for `i : Fin P.card`. This product needs to be shown equal to `∏ i ∈ P, d i`.",
        "Part (b): If `P ≠ Q` and `P.card = Q.card`, then `sub[P,Q] D` will have a zero row. This can be shown by finding an `i ∈ P \ Q`. The corresponding row in `sub[P,Q] D` will be `D (P.orderEmbOfFin rfl i) (Q.orderEmbOfFin rfl j)` for `j : Fin Q.card`. Since `i ∈ P \ Q`, `P.orderEmbOfFin rfl i` is an index in `P` but not in `Q`. For any `j`, `Q.orderEmbOfFin rfl j` is an index in `Q`. Thus, `P.orderEmbOfFin rfl i ≠ Q.orderEmbOfFin rfl j`, making all entries in that row zero. A matrix with a zero row has determinant zero."
